    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>Rich Pin</strong> is a Pinterest Pin that automatically syncs metadata from a linked website. Unlike standard pins, Rich Pins pull real-time data — product price, availability, recipe ingredients, or article details — directly from your site and display it on the pin. They're free to enable and improve discoverability, engagement, and click-through rates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platform</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Pinterest</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Free (business account)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Pinterest's algorithm favours Rich Pins over standard pins in search results and home feed distribution. If you're sharing product content, recipes, or articles on Pinterest without Rich Pins enabled, you're showing up with less information than competitors who have them on — and ranking lower as a result.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a Rich Pin?</h2>
        <p>A Rich Pin is an enhanced Pinterest pin that automatically pulls metadata from a linked webpage and displays it below the pin image. Where a standard pin shows only the image and a description you write manually, a Rich Pin surfaces real-time data directly from your site:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Product Pins:</strong> Real-time price, availability status ("In Stock" / "Sold Out"), and a direct purchase link.</li>
          <li><strong>Recipe Pins:</strong> Ingredient list, serving count, cook time, calorie information, and ratings.</li>
          <li><strong>Article Pins:</strong> Article headline, author name, story description, and publish date.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Rich Pins update automatically when your website data changes. If a product's price drops from $49 to $39, all Product Pins linking to that page update to $39 without any manual action. This real-time accuracy is the core value proposition.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Pinterest's data on Rich Pins</div>
          <p>Pinterest has confirmed that Rich Pins get higher distribution in home feeds and search results because they provide more context for the algorithm to categorise and surface content to relevant users. Product Pins with accurate, real-time pricing data see measurably higher save and click rates than equivalent standard pins.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Rich Pins matter for social media marketing</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Algorithm prioritisation.</strong> Pinterest's feed and search algorithm ranks Rich Pins higher than standard pins because they provide structured, reliable metadata for content categorisation.</li>
          <li><strong>Automatic data sync.</strong> Price changes, stock status updates, and recipe modifications propagate to all existing pins automatically. No manual updating across hundreds of pinned items.</li>
          <li><strong>Richer decision context.</strong> A Product Pin showing "$149 · In Stock" converts browsers to buyers faster than a pin requiring a click just to find the price. More information before the click = higher quality traffic after it.</li>
          <li><strong>SEO within Pinterest.</strong> Rich Pins are more likely to appear in Pinterest search results for specific queries (ingredient searches, product type searches) because of their structured metadata.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation.</strong> Many small businesses have Pinterest accounts but haven't enabled Rich Pins. In the same niche, your Rich Pins compete with a measurable advantage over their standard pins.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Rich Pins work — from setup to display</h2>
        <p>Rich Pins work by reading Open Graph tags or schema.org markup from your website and surfacing that data on the pin. Setup requires three steps:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Add metadata to your website.</strong> Install Open Graph tags (og:title, og:description, og:price:amount, og:availability) or schema.org markup (Product, Recipe, Article) on the relevant pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Validate your metadata.</strong> Submit a page URL to Pinterest's Rich Pin Validator at <code>developers.pinterest.com/tools/url-debugger</code> to confirm your metadata is readable.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply for Rich Pins.</strong> From your Pinterest business account, request Rich Pin approval. Pinterest reviews metadata quality and activates Rich Pins across your existing and future pins within 24-72 hours.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Example Open Graph tags for a Product Rich Pin</span><br>
          &lt;meta property="og:type" content="<span class="uf-new">product</span>" /&gt;<br>
          &lt;meta property="og:title" content="<span class="uf-new">Blue Widget — $149</span>" /&gt;<br>
          &lt;meta property="product:price:amount" content="<span class="uf-new">149.00</span>" /&gt;<br>
          &lt;meta property="product:price:currency" content="<span class="uf-new">USD</span>" /&gt;<br>
          &lt;meta property="product:availability" content="<span class="uf-new">in stock</span>" /&gt;
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Types of Rich Pins — which to use</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Rich Pin type</th><th>Best for</th><th>Data displayed</th><th>Key benefit</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Product Pin</strong></td>
                <td>E-commerce, DTC brands</td>
                <td>Price, availability, purchase link</td>
                <td>Real-time price sync, buy intent capture</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Recipe Pin</strong></td><td>Food blogs, CPG brands, restaurants</td><td>Ingredients, cook time, calories, ratings</td><td>Discovery via ingredient search</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Article Pin</strong></td><td>Publishers, content marketers, blogs</td><td>Headline, author, publish date, description</td><td>Credibility, click-through from search</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Standard Pin</strong></td><td>Brand content without structured data</td><td>Image + manual description only</td><td>Simpler setup, less algorithm advantage</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Rich Pin examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — DTC skincare brand</h3>
        <p>A direct-to-consumer skincare brand enabled Product Rich Pins across their 200+ product pages. All Pinterest saves linking to these pages began displaying real-time pricing and stock status. One Product Pin format tested against their standard pin equivalent achieved 3x more saves and shares within the first month. The real-time "In Stock" indicator reduced abandoned clicks from people who arrived to find out-of-stock products.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — food blog with Recipe Pins</h3>
        <p>A recipe blogger enabled Recipe Rich Pins across 400+ posts. Pinterest began surfacing these pins in ingredient-specific searches ("avocado toast recipes", "30-minute pasta") that the blog hadn't previously ranked for. Monthly Pinterest referral traffic grew 67% over the 6 months following activation, primarily driven by discovery in ingredient-based search queries that the Recipe Pin metadata unlocked.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Rich Pins vs. standard pins vs. promoted pins — which to use</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Rich Pins</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Free to enable</li>
              <li>Auto-syncs website metadata</li>
              <li>Higher algorithm distribution</li>
              <li>Real-time price and stock updates</li>
              <li>Best for product, recipe, and article content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Standard Pins</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No metadata setup required</li>
              <li>Manual description entry</li>
              <li>Lower algorithm prioritisation</li>
              <li>Static — no auto-updates</li>
              <li>Fine for brand/lifestyle content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for Rich Pins</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritise Product Pins if you sell anything.</strong> Price and availability data in the pin itself eliminates a pre-click friction point. Buyers know before clicking whether the product is in budget and in stock.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep your Open Graph tags accurate.</strong> Rich Pins sync to your live metadata. Outdated or inaccurate pricing information on your site will appear on all linked pins immediately. Audit your OG tags regularly.</li>
          <li><strong>Use a Pinterest-optimised image ratio.</strong> Rich Pins display best at a 2:3 ratio (1000 x 1500px). Landscape images get cropped unfavourably in feed display.</li>
          <li><strong>Write keyword-rich descriptions on source pages.</strong> Pinterest uses your page's og:description for the pin description. Write these with search intent in mind — not just for web visitors but for Pinterest users searching by topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Validate before mass-pinning.</strong> Test your metadata on Pinterest's URL Debugger before creating a large number of pins. A metadata error on your product template affects every Product Pin sitewide.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor with Pinterest Analytics.</strong> Track which Rich Pin types drive the most saves, clicks, and conversions in your Pinterest business dashboard. High saves with low clicks indicate strong discovery but weak page relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Update product metadata immediately on price changes.</strong> Flash sales and price drops are most effective when Real-time Product Pin data reflects the new price within minutes, not hours.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — not re-validating after site changes</div>
          <p>Migrating to a new platform, changing your URL structure, or updating your theme can break your Open Graph metadata. If your Rich Pins stop displaying extra data, your website changes likely removed or corrupted the metadata Pinterest was reading. Validate your URLs in Pinterest's debugger any time you make significant site changes.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Rich Pin mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Missing or incorrect Open Graph tags.</strong> No og:type tag means Pinterest can't identify what kind of Rich Pin to apply. Products default to Article Pins, losing price and availability data.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same description across all products.</strong> Pinterest's algorithm and search indexes your og:description for search relevance. Generic descriptions ("Shop our collection") add no search value.</li>
          <li><strong>Not having a Pinterest business account.</strong> Rich Pins require a verified business account. Personal accounts cannot access Rich Pin validation or approval.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Article Pins for content marketing.</strong> Publishers and content marketers often skip Rich Pins because they associate them with e-commerce. Article Pins improve search visibility and credibility for any content type.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting and forgetting.</strong> Pinterest's metadata requirements and Rich Pin specifications update periodically. Check your Rich Pin display quarterly to confirm everything still renders correctly.</li>
        </ul>

